qas.question: Do official political parties exist in a nonpartisan system?

answers.text: In a nonpartisan system, no official political parties exist

qas.question: Was the administration of George Washington nonpartisan?

answers.text: The administration of George Washington and the first few sessions of the United States Congress were nonpartisan.

context: <a0_0>In a nonpartisan system, no official political parties exist<a0_0/>, sometimes reflecting <b4_0>legal restrictions<b4_0/> on political parties. In nonpartisan elections, each candidate is eligible for office on his or her own merits. In nonpartisan legislatures, there are no typically formal party alignments within the legislature. <a1_0>The administration of George Washington and the first few sessions of the United States Congress were nonpartisan.<a1_0/> Washington also <b5_0>warned against<b5_0/> <a2_0>political parties<a2_0/> during his Farewell Address. In the United States, the unicameral legislature of Nebraska is nonpartisan but <b6_0>is elected<b6_0/> and <b7_0>votes<b7_0/> on informal party lines. In Canada, the territorial legislatures of the Northwest Territories and Nunavut are nonpartisan. In New Zealand, Tokelau has a nonpartisan parliament. Many city and county governments[vague] are nonpartisan. <b8_0>Nonpartisan elections and modes of governance<b8_0/> are common outside of state institutions. Unless there are legal prohibitions against political parties, factions within nonpartisan systems often evolve into <a3_0>political parties<a3_0/>.
